  "paper_paragraph": "=== Power Analysis: Minimum Detectable IC ===\n\nWith N=750 daily cross-sectional observations at \u03b1=0.05, the minimum detectable Spearman rank correlation (IC) at 80% power is 0.1021. Our observed IC of 0.0070 (US Ridge) is 6.85% of this threshold and falls well below it. \n\nThis means that even if a true linear predictive relationship existed between our model features and future daily returns, its magnitude would need to exceed IC \u2248 0.1021 to be distinguishable from zero with 80% confidence. The observed near-zero IC is therefore not a failure of statistical power\u2014the design is adequately powered to detect economically meaningful signals. A true IC of 0.1021 corresponds to R\u00b2 \u2248 0.010434, implying that features would need to explain at least 1.0434% of cross-sectional return variance to be detected.\n\nExtending the observation window to N=1,500 would lower the detection threshold to IC \u2248 0.0723, but the qualitative conclusion remains unchanged: the models capture no economically significant cross-sectional return signal.\n\nIn the daily return space (\u03c3 \u2248 2%), the minimum detectable signal corresponds to a cross-sectional return dispersion of approximately 20.4 basis points. By contrast, the observed IC of 0.0070 implies a signal of only 1.4 bps\u2014below transaction costs for all but the most liquid instruments.\n\nInterpretation: The null result is not an artifact of insufficient data. The study is adequately powered; the models genuinely fail to extract predictive signal from the feature set at daily horizons.",
  "methodology": {
    "method": "Fisher z-transformation for Spearman rank correlation",
    "formula": "z = 0.5 * ln((1+r)/(1-r)), SE(z) = 1/sqrt(N-3)",
    "power_equation": "Power = 1 - \u03a6(z_crit - \u03b8) + \u03a6(-z_crit - \u03b8)",
    "theta": "atanh(rho) * sqrt(N-3)",
    "ic_to_rsq": "R\u00b2 \u2248 IC\u00b2 (standardized cross-sectional regression)"
